E-mail: acalle.edul@gmail.com or acallepascual@hotmail.com, Phone 34 91 3303281 Fax 34 91 3303240.</p><p data-class="jrnlDeleted">WC abstract: 250.</p><p data-class="jrnlDeleted">WC manuscript 3900, excluding words in tables, table legends, figure legends, title page, acknowledgments, and references.</p><p data-class="jrnlDeleted"><span data-class="Del cts-1">Tables: 4.</span></p><boxed-text data-id="BLK_BX1" data-stream-name="a_BX1"><caption><title data-id="BX1">Key messages<named-content content-type="del cts-3" alt="preeditor 0cc3574f-ac88-4b19-968b-dc069b047c2c" data-track-detail="">:</named-content></title></caption><title data-class="jrnlBoxHead" contenteditable="true">What is already known about this subject?</title><p data-class-name="SecPara">The numerous health benefits of the Mediterranean Diet (MedDiet) have been repeatedly reproduced. However, there are no published studies evaluating the effect of a MedDiet-based MNT on GDM complications (glycaemic control and pregnancy outcomes) nor comparing these women with those with <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="333" data-match="normal glucose tolerance" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="NGT">normal glucose tolerance</named-content> (<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="ABBR" data-tag-type="ABBR" data-offset="359" data-match=" (NGT)" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="7_1">NGT</named-content>).</p><title data-class="jrnlBoxHead"><named-content content-type="ins cts-3" alt="preeditor 0cc3574f-ac88-4b19-968b-dc069b047c2c" data-track-detail="">What are the new findings?</named-content></title><p data-class-name="SecPara">The results of this secondary analysis indicate that a MedDiet-based </p><list list-content="ul" list-type="disc"><list-item><p data-class-name="SecPara">MNT in women with GDM was effective in obtaining</p></list-item><list-item><p data-class-name="SecPara">Near-Normoglycemia. Women with GDM managed to attain HbA<sub>1c</sub> levels like women with NGT.</p></list-item><list-item><p data-class-name="SecPara"> The rates of several pregnancy outcomes were comparable between women with and without GDM. Conversely, some outcomes such as the rates of <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="373" data-match="insufficient weight gain" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="IWG">insufficient weight gain</named-content> (<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="ABBR" data-tag-type="ABBR" data-offset="399" data-match=" (IWG)" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="8_1">IWG</named-content>) and small for gestational age (<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="ABBR" data-tag-type="ABBR" data-offset="435" data-match=" (SGA)" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="8_2">SGA</named-content>) new-borns were significantly higher in women with GDM.</p></list-item><list-item><p data-class-name="SecPara">These outcomes could be associated with the reduction of dietary intake that usually accompanies GDM diagnosis. When women are diagnosed with GDM they switch from high-density foods to low-density ones.</p></list-item></list><title data-class="jrnlBoxHead" contenteditable="true">How might these results change the focus of research or clinical practice?</title><p data-class-name="SecPara">A Med-Diet based MNT should be considered as a universal first-line therapy in GDM treatment to improve perinatal pregnancy outcomes. However, strategies need to be designed to reduce IWG and SGA new-borns. Diabetes educators should insist on the fact that reducing unhealthy foods in their diets does not imply reducing total caloric intake.</p></boxed-text><title data-level="1" data-class="jrnlHead1" old-class="">Introduction<named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">.</named-content></title><p data-class="jrnlSecPara"><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="0" data-match="Gestational Diabetes Mellitus" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="GDM">Gestational Diabetes Mellitus</named-content> (<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="ABBR" data-tag-type="ABBR" data-offset="31" data-match=" (GDM)" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="11_10">GD<named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preeditor 4b5360d3-99b8-4ec9-a146-5a08ed957262"><named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preeditor 4b5360d3-99b8-4ec9-a146-5a08ed957262">(</named-content><xref ref-type="video" data-citation-string=" V1 " data-init-id="V1" data-cite-type="delete" data-anchor="true" data-track="del">video 1</xref><named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preeditor 4b5360d3-99b8-4ec9-a146-5a08ed957262">)</named-content><xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R1 " data-init-id="R1" data-track="del" data-cite-type="insert"><sup>1</sup></xref><xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R2 " data-init-id="R2" data-track="ins" data-cite-type="insert"><sup>2</sup></xref><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preeditor 4b5360d3-99b8-4ec9-a146-5a08ed957262">∂</named-content></named-content></named-content></p><boxed-text data-remove-label="true" data-id="BLK_BWL2" data-new-float="true" data-stream-name="a_BWL2" insert-citation="false"><caption><title data-id="BWL2">test-caption</title></caption><p>Test - data-match="Medical Nutrition Therapy" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="MNT">Medical Nutrition Therapy</named-content> (<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="ABBR" data-tag-type="ABBR" data-offset="27" data-match=" (MNT)" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="12_5">MNT</named-content>) is first-line therapy in the treatment of GDM.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R7 R8 R9 R10 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="79" data-match="7–10" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="12_1" data-track-change="7&amp;ndash;10"><sup>7–10</sup></xref> Different types of dietary interventions have been compared and evaluated, with inconsistent results.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R11 R12 R13 R14 R15 R16 R17 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="190" data-match="11–17" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="12_2" data-track-change="11&amp;ndash;17"><sup>11–17</sup></xref>The lack of consistent data does not permit evidence-based recommendations, specifically with regards to macronutrient distribution of MNT in GDM management.</p><p>Restricting carbohydrates has been the cornerstone to GDM treatment. However, a less restrictive approach, permitting a higher consumption of complex carbohydrates is being studied as a possible alternative. A Higher–Complex Carbohydrate/Lower Fat <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VERSUS" data-tag-type="VERSUS" data-offset="250" data-match="versus" data-replace="vs" data-pattern="vs" data-tag-index="13_7" data-track-change="versus">v<named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preeditor e08e910d-c111-44ed-9f81-d3874d44cbda" data-track-detail="">ersu</named-content>s</named-content> a Low-Carbohydrate/Higher-Fat seems to improve maternal insulin resistance and infant adiposity.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R11 R12 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="354" data-match="11,12" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="13_1" data-track-change="11,12"><sup>11 12</sup></xref> In parallel, low glycemic-index diets are have also shown benefits in maternal insulin resistance, a lower need of insulin usage and risk of macrosomia.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R15 R16 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="514" data-match="15,16" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="13_2" data-track-change="15,16"><sup>15 16</sup></xref> Consensus panels have not given specific diet recommendations due to this insufficient evidence. However, both the American College of Obstetricians and <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">Gynecologists</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="SPELL" data-tag-type="SPELL" data-offset="675" data-match="Gynecologists" data-replace="Gynaecologists" data-pattern="Gynaecologists" data-tag-index="13_8" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="Gynecologists">Gynaecologists</named-content> (<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="ABBR" data-tag-type="ABBR" data-offset="690" data-match=" (ACOG)" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="13_4">ACOG</named-content>) and Endocrine Society still stand behind low fat diets in GDM treatment. A very recent metanalysis that included 18 <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">randomized</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="SPELL" data-tag-type="SPELL" data-offset="812" data-match="randomized" data-replace="randomised" data-pattern="randomised" data-tag-index="13_9" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="randomized">randomised</named-content> controlled trials showed that dietary interventions as <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">compared to</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="HIGH" data-tag-type="HIGH" data-offset="878" data-match="compared to" data-replace="compared with" data-pattern="compared with" data-tag-index="13_6" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="compared to">compared with</named-content> routine care in GDM management improved perinatal outcomes.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R18 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="950" data-match="18" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="13_3" data-track-change="18"><sup>18</sup></xref> It highlights the importance of nutritional approaches in GDM treatment and the need to evaluate further its effect on perinatal outcomes in order to find the most appropriate MNT.</p><p>The numerous health benefits of the Mediterranean Diet (MedDiet), with a high consumption of extra virgin olive oil and nuts, has been repeatedly reproduced.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R19 R20 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="158" data-match="19,20" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="14_1" data-track-change="19,20"><sup>19 20</sup></xref> A MedDiet-based MNT needs to be examined since it is a diet that has a low-carbohydrate/higher-fat macronutrient distribution, has a low glycaemic index diet and is rich in antioxidants and anti-inflammatory components.</p></disp-quote><disp-quote data-type="pull-quote"><p>In healthy pregnant women, the adherence to this dietary pattern has been associated with a <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="92" data-match="30%" data-replace="30" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="15_3">30</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" perinatal outcomes.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R21 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="185" data-match="21" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="15_1" data-track-change="21"><sup>21</sup></xref> Most studies evaluating MNT focus their attention in assessing different types of MNT as <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">compared to</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="HIGH" data-tag-type="HIGH" data-offset="279" standard-care diets in women with GDM. Only one study group have compared women with <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="376" data-match="normal these women with those with NGT.</p><p>The aim of this study was to explore clinical, biochemical and body weight parameters, as well as maternal and neonatal outcomes, of women with GDM treated with a MedDiet-based MNT <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VERSUS" data-tag-type="VERSUS" data-offset="181" data-match="versus" data-replace="vs" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-type="s-case">Designs</named-content><named-content content-type="ins" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-type="s-case">designs</named-content> and <named-content content-type="del" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-type="s-case">Methods</named-content><named-content content-type="ins" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-type="s-case">methods</named-content><named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">.</named-content></title><title data-level="2" data-class="jrnlHead2" old-class="">Trial <named-content content-type="del" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-type="s-case">Design</named-content><named-content content-type="ins" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-type="s-case">design</named-content><named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">.</named-content></title><disp-quote data-type="pull-quote"><p>The study was a secondary analysis of the St. Carlos GDM Prevention study – a prospective, single centre, <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">randomized</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="SPELL" data-tag-type="SPELL" data-offset="108" data-match="randomized" data-replace="randomised" data-pattern="randomised" data-tag-index="19_9" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="randomized">randomised</named-content> trial with two parallel groups. It targeted all pregnant women followed by the Obstetrics Department of the Hospital Clínico San Carlos (Madrid, Spain) from January <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">1st</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="ORDI" data-tag-type="ORDI" data-offset="285" data-match="1st" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="19_6" data-function="numberToText,addTrackChanges" data-track-change="1st">first</named-content> through December 31st, <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="THSE" data-tag-type="THSE" data-offset="312" data-match="2015" data-replace="2015" data-pattern="2015" data-tag-index="19_5">2015</named-content>. A detailed description of the <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="LQUOTE" data-tag-type="LQUOTE" data-offset="348" data-match="“" data-replace="“" data-pattern="“" data-tag-index="19_7"><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preeditor e08e910d-c111-44ed-9f81-d3874d44cbda" data-track-detail="">‘</named-content></named-content>St. Carlos Gestational GDM prevention study<named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preeditor e08e910d-c111-44ed-9f81-d3874d44cbda" data-track-detail="">’</named-content><span data-class="jrnlDeleted" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="RQUOTE" data-tag-type="RQUOTE" data-offset="394" data-match="”" data-replace="”" data-pattern="”" data-tag-index="19_8" data-track="del" data-modified="Remove empty tag"/> has been previously published.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R21 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="429" data-match="21" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="19_1" data-track-change="21"><sup>21</sup></xref> In summary, participants were <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">randomized</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="SPELL" data-tag-type="SPELL" data-offset="464" data-match="randomized" data-replace="randomised" data-pattern="randomised" data-tag-index="19_10" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="randomized">randomised</named-content> at 12<s> </s><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="481" data-match="gestational weeks" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="GW">gestational weeks</named-content> to a control or intervention group. At this point, the intervention started. The research team did not impose any nutritional recommendations on the control group. This group received nutritional recommendations provided in regular clinical practice by obstetricians and midwifes. Current guidelines recommend limiting the consumption of all fats which by default include extra virgin olive oil and nuts. data-track-detail="">.</named-content></title><p data-class="jrnlSecPara">Discrete variables are presented with their frequency and percentage distribution, continuous variables by their mean and standard deviation (<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAR,OPR,VAL,OPRS,VALS,UNT" data-tag-type="OPR" data-offset="142" data-match="±SD" All primary analyses were performed on an intention-to-treat basis. Comparison between groups for categorical variables was evaluated using the χ<sup>2</sup> test or Fisher's exact test. For continuous variables, measures were compared with Student’s t test or the Mann–Whitney U test if distribution of quantitative variables was not normal, as verified by the Shapiro-Wilk test.</p><p for the secondary binary outcomes. To evaluate the effect of the study group on the association of diabetes with the secondary outcome variables, the interaction term was introduced in the model.</p><p data-class="jrnlSecPara">All <italic>P</italic> values are 2-tailed at less than 0.05. Analyses were performed using SPSS, version 21 (Chicago, Illinois).</p><title data-level="1" data-class="jrnlHead1" old-class="">Results</title><title data-level="2" data-class="jrnlHead2" old-class="">Participant’s characteristics<named-content content-type="del cts-3" alt="preeditor 0cc3574f-ac88-4b19-968b-dc069b047c2c" data-track-detail="">.</named-content></title><p data-class="jrnlSecPara">In the St. Carlos GDM Prevention study, a total of <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="THSE" data-tag-type="THSE" data-offset="51" data-match="1501" data-replace="1501" data-pattern="1501" data-tag-index="44_6">1501</named-content> women attending their first ultrasound visit were eligible; <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="THSE" data-tag-type="THSE" data-offset="116" data-match="1000" data-replace="1000" data-pattern="1000" data-tag-index="44_7">1000</named-content> accepted participation and signed the consent form. They were randomly allocated to the control (<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAR,OPR,VAL,OPRS,VALS,UNT" data-tag-type="VAR" data-offset="218" data-match="n=500" data-replace="n" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="44_4" data-function="lowercase,removeItalics">n</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAR,OPR,VAL,OPRS,VALS,UNT" data-tag-type="OPR" data-offset="219" data-match="n=500" data-replace="=" data-pattern="$2" data-tag-index="44_4">=</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAR,OPR,VAL,OPRS,VALS,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="220" data-match="n=500" data-replace="500" data-pattern="$3" data-tag-index="44_4">500</named-content>) or intervention group (<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAR,OPR,VAL,OPRS,VALS,UNT" data-tag-type="VAR" data-offset="248" data-match="n=500" data-replace="n" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="44_5" data-function="lowercase,removeItalics">n</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAR,OPR,VAL,OPRS,VALS,UNT" data-tag-type="OPR" data-offset="249" data-match="n=500" data-replace="=" data-pattern="$2" data-tag-index="44_5">=</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAR,OPR,VAL,OPRS,VALS,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="250" data-match="n=500" data-replace="500" data-pattern="$3" data-tag-index="44_5">500</named-content>). Sixty women in the control group and 66 women in the intervention group were lost to follow-up before GDM screening. Consequently, 874 women were followed through postpartum discharge and included in the final analysis. A total of <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="PER,VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="PER" data-offset="487" data-match="177 (20%" data-replace="177" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="44_2">177</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="PER,VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="490" data-match="177 (20%" data-replace=" (20%" data-pattern=" $2" data-tag-index="44_2"> (20%</named-content>, 103 from control group and 74 from intervention group) developed GDM and the remaining <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="PER,VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="PER" data-offset="584" data-match="697 (80%" data-replace="697" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="44_3">697</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="PER,VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="587" data-match="697 (80%" data-replace=" (80%" data-pattern=" $2" data-tag-index="44_3"> (80%</named-content>, 337 from control group and 360 from intervention group) had NGT (<xref ref-type="supplementary-material" data-citation-string=" " data-tag-desc="SUPPLFTREF" data-tag-type="SUPPLFTREF" data-offset="659" data-match="Supplemental Figure S1" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="44_1" data-track="del">Supplemental Figure S1</xref><xref ref-type="supplementary-material" data-citation-string=" SP2 " data-track="ins">online supplementary file 2</xref><xref ref-type="supplementary-material" data-citation-string=" ST1 " data-cite-type="delete" data-anchor="true">online supplementary table 1</xref><named-content content-type="del cts-3" alt="preeditor 0cc3574f-ac88-4b19-968b-dc069b047c2c" data-track-detail="">)</named-content>. These were included in this secondary analysis.</p><p data-class="jrnlSecPara"><xref ref-type="table" data-citation-string=" T1 " data-offset="0" data-match="Table 1" data-track="del"><named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">Table 1</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail=""><named-content content-type="changeCase sty cts-3" alt="preeditor 0cc3574f-ac88-4b19-968b-dc069b047c2c" data-track-detail="" data-track-hint="UPPERCASE Added">T<span data-class="hidden" hidden-track="track">t</span></named-content>able 1</named-content></xref><xref ref-type="table" data-citation-string=" T1 T2 " data-init-id="T1,T2" data-track="ins" data-cite-type="insert" data-anchor="true">Tables 1 and 2</xref> shows baseline demographic and clinical characteristics of the women of the two cohorts, according to glucose tolerance. content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAR,OPR,VAL,OPRS,VALS,UNT" data-tag-type="ABBRV" data-offset="17" data-match="Mean ± SD or" data-replace="SD" data-pattern="SD" data-tag-index="559_1">SD</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAR,OPR,VAL,OPRS,VALS,UNT" data-tag-type="UNT" data-offset="19" data-match="Mean ± SD or" data-replace=" or" data-pattern=" $6" data-tag-index="559_1" data-track-change=" or"> or</named-content> number (%).</p></fn><fn data-class="jrnlTblFoot" data-id="T4_FN4" fn-type="linked-fn" data-track="del"><label data-class="jrnlFNLabel">*</label><p><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preeditor 4b5360d3-99b8-4ec9-a146-5a08ed957262">hello</named-content></p></fn><fn data-class="jrnlTblFoot" data-id="T4_FN3" fn-type="abbrev" data-def-list="true"><p><def-list><def-item data-class="jrnlTblDefItem" data-channel="components" data-event="click" data-message="{'funcToCall': 'populateAbbrevFootNote', 'param' : {'component' : 'jrnlAbbrevFoot'}}" fn-type="abbrev" age</p></def>;</def-item><def-item data-class="jrnlTblDefItem" data-channel="components" data-event="click" data-message="{'funcToCall': 'populateAbbrevFootNote', 'param' : {'component' : remove-last-node-suffix="true" set-last-node-suffix="."><p><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="127" data-match="gestational diabetes mellitus" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="GDM">gestational diabetes </named-content></p></def>;</def-item><def-item data-class="jrnlTblDefItem" data-channel="components" data-event="click" data-message="{'funcToCall': 'populateAbbrevFootNote', 'param' : {'component' : 'jrnlAbbrevFoot'}}" fn-type="abbrev" data-id="T4_FN3"><term data-class="jrnlAbbrevTerm">GW</term>, <def data-class="jrnlFootDefinition" remove-last-node-suffix="true" set-last-node-suffix="."><p><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="162" data-match="gestational weeks" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="GW">gestational week</named-content></p></def>;</def-item><def-item data-class="jrnlTblDefItem" data-channel="components" data-event="click" data-message="{'funcToCall': 'populateAbbrevFootNote', 'param' : {'component' : 'jrnlAbbrevFoot'}}" fn-type="abbrev" data-id="T4_FN3"><term data-class="jrnlAbbrevTerm">IWG</term>, <def data-class="jrnlFootDefinition" remove-last-node-suffix="true" set-last-node-suffix="."><p><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="186" data-match="insufficient weight gain" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="IWG">insufficient weight gain</named-content></p></def>;</def-item><def-item data-class="jrnlTblDefItem" data-channel="components" data-event="click" data-message="{'funcToCall': 'populateAbbrevFootNote', 'param' : {'component' : 'jrnlAbbrevFoot'}}" fn-type="abbrev" data-id="T4_FN3" data-track="del"><term data-class="jrnlAbbrevTerm">OR</term>, <def data-class="jrnlFootDefinition" remove-last-node-suffix="true" set-last-node-suffix="."><p>odds ratio</p></def>;</def-item><def-item data-class="jrnlTblDefItem" data-channel="components" data-event="click" data-message="{'funcToCall': 'populateAbbrevFootNote', 'param' : {'component' : 'jrnlAbbrevFoot'}}" fn-type="abbrev" data-id="T4_FN3"><term data-class="jrnlAbbrevTerm">SGA</term>, <def data-class="jrnlFootDefinition" remove-last-node-suffix="true" set-last-node-suffix="."><p>small for gestational age</p></def>.</def-item></def-list></p></fn></table-wrap-foot></table-wrap><title data-level="1" data-class="jrnlHead1" old-class="">Conclusions<named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">.</named-content></title><p data-class="jrnlSecPara">After <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="6" data-match="3 months" data-replace="3" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="54_2">3</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="UNT" data-offset="7" data-match="3 months" data-replace=" months" data-pattern=" $2" data-tag-index="54_2"> months</named-content> of treatment with a MedDiet as MNT, glycaemic control (measured by HbA1c) in GDMw was not inferior to that of NGTw. To our knowledge, this is the first study that shows that with GDM management, using a MedDiet-based MNT, GDMw had similar glycaemic control at <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,RNGS,RNGC,RNGE,UNT" data-tag-type="RNGS" data-offset="275" data-match="36-38" data-replace="36" data-pattern="$2" data-tag-index="54_1">36</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,RNGS,RNGC,RNGE,UNT" data-tag-type="RNGC" data-offset="277" data-match="36-38" data-replace="–" data-pattern="–" data-tag-index="54_1" data-track-change="-">–</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,RNGS,RNGC,RNGE,UNT" data-tag-type="RNGE" data-offset="278" data-match="36-38" data-replace="38" data-pattern="$4" data-tag-index="54_1">38</named-content> <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="281" data-match="gestational weeks" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="GW">gestational weeks</named-content> to NGTw. As expected given glycaemic control, no significant differences were observed in the rates of excessive weight gain, pregnancy induced hypertension, type of delivery, perineal trauma, prematurity and LGA new-borns when comparing GDMw and NGTw.</p><p data-class="jrnlSecPara">Only <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="5" data-match="27%" data-replace="27" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="55_3">27</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="UNT" data-offset="7" data-match="27%" data-replace="%" data-pattern="%" data-tag-index="55_3">%</named-content> of GDMw needed insulin therapy after failure of MNT. This observed rate is lower than rates described in other studies, around <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="136" data-match="56.7%" data-replace="56.7" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="55_4">56.7</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="UNT" data-offset="140" data-match="56.7%" data-replace="%" data-pattern="%" data-tag-index="55_4">%</named-content> in Caucasian women<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="162" data-match="26" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="55_1" data-citation-string=" R26 " data-track-change="26"><sup>26</sup></xref> and <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="170" data-match="50%" data-replace="50" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="55_5">50</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="UNT" data-offset="172" data-match="50%" data-replace="%" data-pattern="%" data-tag-index="55_5">%</named-content> in other regions of Spain.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="201" data-match="27" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="55_2" data-citation-string=" R27 " data-track-change="27"><sup>27</sup></xref></p><p data-class="jrnlSecPara">A continuous relationship between maternal glycemia and adverse maternal and neonatal outcomes is well documented.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="115" data-match="1" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="56_1" data-citation-string=" R1 " data-track-change="1"><sup>1</sup></xref> LGA new-borns, macrosomia and C-sections are the outcomes most linked to GDM and poor glycaemic control, as well as to maternal obesity and gestational weight gain<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="284" data-match="28-31" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="56_2" data-citation-string=" R28 R29 R30 R31 " data-track-change="28-31"><sup>28–31</sup></xref> In a large prospective study, high maternal BMI rather than hyperglycaemia was associated with LGA new-borns.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="401" data-match="32" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="56_3" data-citation-string=" R32 " data-track-change="32"><sup>32</sup></xref> However, our results revealed that, despite GDMw having a higher BMI at baseline, LGA and macrosomia rates were similar in GDMw and NGTw. Therefore, GDM management, that includes a MedDiet-based MNT, is associated with a lower incidence of these outcomes, possibly by inducing lower rates of excessive weight gain.</p><p data-class="jrnlSecPara">Most of the adverse pregnancy outcomes evaluated were similar between GDMw and NGTw. However, rates of NICU admissions, <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="120" data-match="insufficient weight gain" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="IWG">insufficient weight gain</named-content>, SGA new-borns and urinary tract infections were higher in the GDMw. The higher rates of NICU admission are concurrent with results from a retrospective cohort.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="306" data-match="22" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="57_1" data-citation-string=" R22 " data-track-change="22"><sup>22</sup></xref></p><p data-class="jrnlSecPara">While rates of excessive weight gain were lower in the GDMw than in NGTw, rates of <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="83" data-match="insufficient weight gain" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="IWG">insufficient weight gain</named-content> were significantly higher. One possible explanation is that following GDM diagnosis and, consequently, the care and advise provided women reduce energy intake, substituting high energy-dense foods for healthier food options.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="333" data-match="7" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="58_1" data-citation-string=" R7 " data-track-change="7"><sup>7</sup></xref> Another potential explanation is the fact that GDMw self-monitor blood glucose. Undoubtedly, it is an indispensable tool in improving glycaemic control and permits the tailoring of MNT to each individual.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="542" data-match="33" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="58_2" data-citation-string=" R33 " data-track-change="33"><sup>33</sup></xref> However, the downside of self-monitoring blood glucose is women’s attitude towards not achieving tight glycaemic control and concern that hyperglycaemia could lead to insulin therapy<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="733" data-match="34,35" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="58_3" data-citation-string=" R34 R35 " data-track-change="34,35"><sup>34 35</sup></xref> Women could thus restrict the consumption of the foods associated with higher glucose levels, and limit carbohydrate/caloric intake. In fact, when present, <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="896" data-match="insufficient weight gain" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="IWG">insufficient weight gain</named-content> occurred within the first weeks of self-monitoring of blood glucose, prior to insulin initiation, and therefore did not seem to be related to insulin therapy <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="FNW" data-tag-type="FNW" data-offset="1079" data-match="per se" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="58_4" data-function="removeItalics">per se</named-content> (Data not shown).</p><p data-class="jrnlSecPara">Determining appropriate gestational weight gain in overweight and obese women is an ongoing debate<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="100" data-match="12,13,23,36-38" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="59_1" data-citation-string=" R12 R13 R23 R36 R37 R38 " data-track-change="12,13,23,36-38"><sup>12 13 23 36–38</sup></xref> There is rising evidence that a lower gestational weight gain than that recommended by the Institute of Medicine in overweight and obese women reduces the risk for LGA neonates, macrosomia, preeclampsia and c-sections<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="335" data-match="37" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="59_2" data-citation-string=" R37 " data-track-change="37"><sup>37</sup></xref> A systematic review and meta-analysis reported higher rates of SGA and lower rates of LGA in overweight women who lost weight during pregnancy.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="483" data-match="23" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="59_3" data-citation-string=" R23 " data-track-change="23"><sup>23</sup></xref> Similarly, a recent systematic review and meta-analysis associated <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="555" data-match="insufficient weight gain" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="IWG">insufficient weight gain</named-content> with higher rates of SGA and prematurity and with lower rates of LGA and macrosomia.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="665" data-match="31" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="59_4" data-citation-string=" R31 " data-track-change="31"><sup>31</sup></xref> These data agree with those reported in the present study. The effect of <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="743" data-match="insufficient weight gain" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="IWG">insufficient weight gain</named-content> on SGA is still controversial and needs to be further studied. In any case, given the higher rates of <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="870" data-match="insufficient weight gain" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="IWG">insufficient weight gain</named-content> and SGA new-borns we have found strategies should be designed to try to avoid the occurrence of both.</p><p data-class="jrnlSecPara">Rates of urinary tract infections were significantly higher in GDMw than in NGTw. Maternal urinary tract infections could have facilitated higher rates of SGA new-borns, since they have been independently associated with prematurity and restricted intrauterine growth<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R39 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="269" data-match="39" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="60_1" data-track-change="39"><sup>39</sup></xref> In addition, women who had urinary tract infections required antibiotic treatment, potentially leading to changes in the microbiota that could induce higher rates of SGA new-borns<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R40 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="454" data-match="40" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="60_2" data-track-change="40"><sup>40</sup></xref> Furthermore, E.coli has been associated with SGA new-borns secondary to placental insufficiency and a higher risk of prematurity<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R41 R42 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="588" data-match="41,42" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="60_3" data-track-change="41,42"><sup>41 42</sup></xref></p><p data-class="jrnlSecPara">As <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">compared to</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="HIGH" data-tag-type="HIGH" data-offset="3" data-match="compared to" data-replace="compared with" data-pattern="compared with" data-tag-index="61_8" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="compared to">compared with</named-content> other studies, our rates of insulin therapy were the lowest. A low-carbohydrate diet, with a carbohydrate content of 40%, similar to ours, was not associated with lower rates on insulin treatments as <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">compared to</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="HIGH" data-tag-type="HIGH" data-offset="215" data-match="compared to" data-replace="compared with" data-pattern="compared with" data-tag-index="61_9" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="compared to">compared with</named-content> a control diet in women with GDM.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="261" data-match="27" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="61_1" data-citation-string=" R27 " data-track-change="27"><sup>27</sup></xref> In addition, pregnancy outcomes were found to be similar between groups. Rates of SGA, macrosomia, c-sections and maternal hypertension were lower in our group of women with GDM as <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">compared to</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="HIGH" data-tag-type="HIGH" data-offset="447" data-match="compared to" data-replace="compared with" data-pattern="compared with" data-tag-index="61_10" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="compared to">compared with</named-content> women allocated to the low-carbohydrate diet.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="505" data-match="27" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="61_2" data-citation-string=" R27 " data-track-change="27"><sup>27</sup></xref> This is so despite similarities in total caloric distribution of carbohydrates in our study and theirs. These differences could be attributed to the quality of fats consumed by our subjects, whose diet was rich in EVOO and nuts. They could also be attributed to the high content in fruits and vegetables. In fact, a recent systematic review and metanalysis revealed that using DASH diets as MNT in GDM was associated with improvements in HOMA-IR, medication need and macrosomia.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="990" data-match="18" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="61_3" data-citation-string=" R18 " data-track-change="18"><sup>18</sup></xref> Moreover, low glycaemic index diets have shown to reduce <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">birthweight</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="HIGH" data-tag-type="HIGH" data-offset="1052" data-match="birthweight" data-replace="birth weight" data-pattern="birth weight" data-tag-index="61_11" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="birthweight">birth weight</named-content>, risk of macrosomia and need for medication. However, results from studies testing different dietary interventions in GDM treatment indicate that mean <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">birthweight</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="HIGH" data-tag-type="HIGH" data-offset="1215" data-match="birthweight" data-replace="birth weight" data-pattern="birth weight" data-tag-index="61_12" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="birthweight">birth weight</named-content> in their studied sample was found to be higher than the one found in our women with GDM, including those following a low carbohydrate<sup>12</sup> and low-glycaemic index diet.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="1393" data-match="17" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="61_4" data-citation-string=" R17 " data-track-change="17"><sup>17</sup></xref> Yamamoto <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="ETL" data-tag-type="ETL" data-offset="1407" data-match="et al" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="61_6" data-function="addItalics" data-track-change="et al"><italic>et al</italic></named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="ETLDOT" data-tag-type="ETLDOT" data-offset="1412" data-match="." data-replace="delete" data-pattern="delete" data-tag-index="61_7"><named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">.</named-content></named-content>, concluded that neither a fat-modification nor low-carbohydrate diet modifies outcomes such as HbA1c, HOMA-IR, insulin need, or neonatal <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">birthweight</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="HIGH" data-tag-type="HIGH" data-offset="1551" data-match="birthweight" data-replace="birth weight" data-pattern="birth weight" data-tag-index="61_13" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="birthweight">birth weight</named-content>, macrosomia and large-for-gestational-age.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="1606" data-match="18" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="61_5" data-citation-string=" R18 " data-track-change="18"><sup>18</sup></xref> However, our results show that levels of HbA1c and HOMA-IR after GDM diagnosis and treatment is comparable to that of healthy women without GDM and so were rates of <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">birthweight</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="HIGH" data-tag-type="HIGH" data-offset="1776" data-match="birthweight" data-replace="birth weight" data-pattern="birth weight" data-tag-index="61_14" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="birthweight">birth weight</named-content>, rates of macrosomia and LGA.</p><p data-class="jrnlSecPara">While our study does not <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="HIGH" data-tag-type="HIGH" data-offset="25" data-match="compare" data-replace="compare" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="62_1" data-function="addTrackChanges">compare</named-content> one nutritional approach to another in GDM treatment, the maternofoetal outcomes found in our study seem to be promising when <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">compared to</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="HIGH" data-tag-type="HIGH" data-offset="159" data-match="compared to" data-replace="compared with" data-pattern="compared with" data-tag-index="62_2" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="compared to">compared with</named-content> those found in other studies that used different types MNT. It is important to consider that our results are being <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">compared to</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="HIGH" data-tag-type="HIGH" data-offset="286" data-match="compared to" data-replace="compared with" data-pattern="compared with" data-tag-index="62_3" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="compared to">compared with</named-content> studies whose population were mainly women of high risk - mostly high BMI and/or metabolic risk factors<s fontsize="12.0">. </s>This means that baseline characteristics between our group of women are not like those of others and therefore making comparisons of our outcomes to that of others is not accurate enough</p><p data-class="jrnlSecPara">This study seems to suggest that MNT based on a MedDiet enhanced with extra virgin olive oil and nuts, thus with a high fat content, is associated with glycaemic control and with a reduction in GDM-related adverse perinatal outcomes. Further studies are needed to confirm our findings. It would be ideal to conduct a RCT specifically designed to evaluate the effect of a MedDiet MNT on glycaemic control and perinatal outcomes in addition to assessing the cause of IWG in GDM women.</p><title data-level="1" data-class="jrnlHead1" old-class="">Limitations<named-content content-type="del cts-3" alt="preeditor 0cc3574f-ac88-4b19-968b-dc069b047c2c" data-track-detail="">.</named-content></title><p data-class="jrnlSecPara">Some limitations were found in this study. First, this was a post-hoc analysis and therefore the original objective of the study was not to evaluate the efficacy of MNT in controlling glycemia in GDMw. Moreover, the data available of the diet of pregnant women gives qualitative rather than quantitative information. Exact caloric and macronutrient intake is lacking because in GDM management women are not provided with a diet with a specific daily total caloric intake. They are given nutritional counselling on what foods to eat and the approximate quantity in which they should eat them, not a strict meal plan. Another limitation is that some of the GDMw had been allocated to the intervention group, prior to GDM diagnosis. The nutritional recommendations given to women of the intervention group were like the ones provided in GDM management. Therefore, women belonging to the intervention group who later developed GDM<named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preeditor 2ebeacb3-1539-4652-8384-ad11baf93c2b" data-track-detail="">(<xref ref-type="fig" data-citation-string=" F2 " data-cite-type="insert" data-anchor="true" data-track="del">figure 2</xref><xref ref-type="fig" data-citation-string=" F1 " data-track="ins" data-cite-type="insert">figure 1</xref><named-content data-class="jrnlQueryRef" data-type="end" content-type="jrnlQueryRef"/><named-content data-class="jrnlQueryRef" data-type="end" content-type="jrnlQueryRef"/><named-content data-class="jrnlQueryRef" data-type="end" content-type="jrnlQueryRef"/>)</named-content> (77/177) had been following recommendations of MedDiet with enhanced consumption of extra virgin olive oil and pistachios for a longer period than those belonging to the<named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preeditor 2ebeacb3-1539-4652-8384-ad11baf93c2b" data-track-detail="">(<xref ref-type="fig" data-citation-string=" F2 " data-cite-type="insert"><named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preeditor 4b5360d3-99b8-4ec9-a146-5a08ed957262">figure 2</named-content><span data-class="cts-1" data-track="del">figure 2A,B</span><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preeditor 4b5360d3-99b8-4ec9-a146-5a08ed957262">figure 2A</named-content></xref>)</named-content> control group. Nevertheless, we observed no interaction in perinatal outcomes between women of the control and intervention group who later developed GDM.</p><fig data-id="BLK_F1" data-stream-name="a_F1" data-new-float="true" data-page-num="4" data-position="bottom" data-top-gap="15pt" data-bot-gap="20pt" data-left-gap="12pt" data-right-gap="12pt" data-column-start="1" data-column-span="1" 2</label><caption><title data-id="F2"/></caption><graphic data-primary-extension="tif" data-original-name="perfect" data-filesize="1.399MB" data-colorspace="sRGB" data-geometry="1772x1055+0+0"/></fig><p data-class="jrnlSecPara">In summary, comprehensive management of GDM, using a MedDiet-based MNT, is associated with the achievement of similar HbA1c levels at <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,RNGS,RNGC,RNGE,UNT" data-tag-type="RNGS" data-offset="134" data-match="36-38" data-replace="36" data-pattern="$2" data-tag-index="66_1">36</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,RNGS,RNGC,RNGE,UNT" data-tag-type="RNGC" data-offset="136" data-match="36-38" data-replace="–" data-pattern="–" data-tag-index="66_1" data-track-change="-">–</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,RNGS,RNGC,RNGE,UNT" data-tag-type="RNGE" data-offset="137" data-match="36-38" data-replace="38" data-pattern="$4" data-tag-index="66_1">38</named-content> <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="140" data-match="gestational weeks" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="GW">gestational weeks</named-content> as that of women with NGT. Some GDM-related perinatal complications were not different between GDMw and NGTw. Notwithstanding the higher rates of SGA new-borns and <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="322" data-match="insufficient weight gain" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="IWG">insufficient weight gain</named-content>, the fact that there were no differences in the rates of excessive weight gain, pregnancy induced hypertension, type of delivery, perineal trauma, prematurity and LGA new-borns is an important finding. This indicates the potential benefit of using this type of diet as MNT in women with GDM. However, strategies are needed to reduce the rates of SGA new-borns and IWG and, thus, avoid their deleterious consequences.</p><p data-class="jrnlDeleted">Acknowledgements.</p><p data-class="jrnlDeleted">Duality of interest: No potential conflicts of interest relevant to this article were reported.</p><p data-class="jrnlDeleted">Author Contributions.</p><p data-class="jrnlDeleted">Conceptualization: A. <abstract>¶
<title data-level="1">A<named-content content-type="changeCase sty cts-3" alt="preeditor 0cc3574f-ac88-4b19-968b-dc069b047c2c" data-track-detail="" data-track-hint="lowercase Added">bstract<span data-class="hidden" hidden-track="track">BSTRACT</span></named-content></title>¶
<title data-level="2">Objective<named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">:</named-content></title>¶
<p>To assess whether MedDiet-based Medical Nutrition Therapy facilitates near-normoglycemia in women with Gestational diabetes mellitus (<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="ABBR" data-tag-type="ABBR" data-offset="134" data-match=" (GDMw)" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="1_1">GDMw</named-content>) and observe the effects on adverse pregnancy outcomes.</p>¶
<title data-level="2">Research <named-content content-type="del" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-type="s-case">Design</named-content><named-content content-type="ins" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-type="s-case">design</named-content> and <named-content content-type="del" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-type="s-case">Methods</named-content><named-content content-type="ins" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-type="s-case">methods</named-content><named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">:</named-content></title>¶
<p>A secondary analysis of the St Carlos GDM Prevention Study, conducted between January-December 2015 in the Hospital Clínico San Carlos (Madrid, Spain). One thousand consecutive normoglycemic women were included before 12 gestational week (<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="ABBR" data-tag-type="ABBR" data-offset="240" data-match=" (GW)" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="2_5">GW</named-content>), with 874 included in final analysis: Of these, 177 women were <named-content content-type="ins cts-4" alt="preeditor 17cca8a6-b929-4611-a9b1-78ad26490e43"><span><ext-link data-class="jrnlExtLink" data-message="{'click':{'funcToCall': 'contentEvt','channel':'components','topic':'general'}}" data-href="http://acallepascual@hotmail.com">acallepascual@hotmail.com</ext-link></span> </named-content>diagnosed with GDM and 697 had Normal Glucose Tolerance (<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="ABBR" data-tag-type="ABBR" data-offset="364" data-match=" (NGT)" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="2_6">NGT</named-content>). All GDMw received MedDiet-based Medical Nutrition Therapy with a recommended daily <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="HYPPRE" data-tag-type="HYPPRE" data-offset="453" data-match="extra-" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="2_8">extra-</named-content>virgin olive oil intake<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAR,OPR,VAL,OPRS,VALS,UNT" data-tag-type="OPR" data-offset="482" data-match="intake ≥40 ml" data-replace=" ≥" data-pattern=" $2" data-tag-index="2_2" data-track-change=" ≥"> ≥</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAR,OPR,VAL,OPRS,VALS,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="486" data-match="intake ≥40 ml" data-replace="40" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="2_2">40</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAR,OPR,VAL,OPRS,VALS,UNT" data-tag-type="UNT" data-offset="488" data-match="intake ≥40 ml" data-replace=" mL" data-pattern=" $2" data-tag-index="2_2" data-track-change=" ml"> mL</named-content> and a daily handful of nuts. The primary goal was comparison of HbA<sub>1c</sub> levels at <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,RNGS,RNGC,RNGE,UNT" data-tag-type="RNGS" data-offset="572" data-match="36-38" data-replace="36" data-pattern="$2" data-tag-index="2_3">36</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,RNGS,RNGC,RNGE,UNT" data-tag-type="RNGC" data-offset="574" data-match="36-38" data-replace="–" data-pattern="–" data-tag-index="2_3" data-track-change="-">–</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,RNGS,RNGC,RNGE,UNT" data-tag-type="RNGE" data-offset="575" data-match="36-38" data-replace="38" data-pattern="$4" data-tag-index="2_3">38</named-content> GWs in GDMw and NGTw.</p>¶
<title data-level="2">Results<named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">:</named-content></title>¶
<p>GDMw as <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">compared to</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" <title data-level="2">Conclusions<named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">:</named-content></title>¶
<p>using a MedDiet-based Medical Nutrition Therapy as part of GDM management, is associated with achievement of Near-Normoglycemia, subsequently making most pregnancy outcomes like those of NGTw.</p>¶

<body>¶
<p data-class="jrnlDeleted">RUNING TITLE: Mediterranean Diet in GDM Treatment.</p>¶
<p data-class="jrnlDeleted">Address correspondence to Dr. Alfonso L. Calle-Pascual, Professor Martin Lagos s/n, Hospital Clínico San Carlos, Endocrinology and Nutrition Department, 1ª Sur. E-28040 Madrid, Spain. E-mail: acalle.edul@gmail.com or acallepascual@hotmail.com, Phone 34 91 3303281 Fax 34 91 3303240.</p>¶
<p data-class="jrnlDeleted">WC abstract: 250.</p>¶
<p data-class="jrnlDeleted">WC manuscript 3900, excluding words in tables, table legends, figure legends, title page, acknowledgments, and references.</p>¶
<p data-class="jrnlDeleted">¶
<span data-class="Del cts-1">Tables: 4.</span>¶
</p>¶
<boxed-text data-id="BLK_BX1" data-stream-name="a_BX1"><caption><title data-id="BX1">Key messages<named-content content-type="del cts-3" alt="preeditor 0cc3574f-ac88-4b19-968b-dc069b047c2c" data-track-detail="">:</named-content></title></caption><title data-class="jrnlBoxHead" contenteditable="true">What is already known about this subject?</title><list list-content="ul" list-type="disc"><list-item><p data-class-name="SecPara">The numerous health benefits of the Mediterranean Diet (MedDiet) have been repeatedly reproduced. However, there are no published studies evaluating the effect of a MedDiet-based MNT on GDM complications (glycaemic control and pregnancy outcomes) nor comparing these women with those with <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="333" data-match="normal glucose tolerance" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="NGT">normal glucose tolerance</named-content> (<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="ABBR" data-tag-type="ABBR" data-offset="359" data-match=" (NGT)" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="7_1">NGT</named-content>).</p></list-item></list><title data-class="jrnlBoxHead">¶
<named-content content-type="ins cts-3" alt="preeditor 0cc3574f-ac88-4b19-968b-dc069b047c2c" data-track-detail="">What are the new findings?</named-content>¶
</title><p data-class-name="SecPara">The results of this secondary analysis indicate that a MedDiet-based </p><list list-content="ul" list-type="disc">¶
<list-item>¶
<p data-class-name="SecPara">MNT in women with GDM was effective in obtaining</p>¶
</list-item>¶
<list-item>¶
<p data-class-name="SecPara">Near-Normoglycemia. Women with GDM managed to attain HbA<sub>1c</sub> levels like women with NGT.</p>¶
</list-item>¶
<list-item>¶
<p data-class-name="SecPara"> The rates of several pregnancy outcomes were comparable between women with and without GDM. Conversely, some outcomes such as the rates of <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="373" data-match="insufficient weight gain" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="IWG">insufficient weight gain</named-content> (<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="ABBR" data-tag-type="ABBR" data-offset="399" data-match=" (IWG)" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="8_1">IWG</named-content>) and small for gestational age (<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="ABBR" data-tag-type="ABBR" data-offset="435" data-match=" (SGA)" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="8_2">SGA</named-content>) new-borns were significantly higher in women with GDM.</p>¶
</list-item>¶
<list-item>¶
<p data-class-name="SecPara">These outcomes could be associated with the reduction of dietary intake that usually accompanies GDM diagnosis. When women are diagnosed with GDM they switch from high-density foods to low-density ones.</p>¶
</list-item>¶
</list><title data-class="jrnlBoxHead" contenteditable="true">How might these results change the focus of research or clinical practice?</title><p data-class-name="SecPara">A Med-Diet based MNT should be considered as a universal first-line therapy in GDM treatment to improve perinatal pregnancy outcomes. However, strategies need to be designed to reduce IWG and SGA new-borns. Diabetes educators should insist on the fact that reducing unhealthy foods in their diets does not imply reducing total caloric intake.</p></boxed-text>¶
<title data-level="1" data-class="jrnlHead1" old-class="">Introduction<named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">.</named-content></title><list list-content="ul" list-type="disc"><list-item><p><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="0" data-match="Gestational Diabetes Mellitus" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="GDM">Gestational Diabetes Mellitus</named-content> (<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="ABBR" data-tag-type="ABBR" data-offset="31" data-match=" (GDM)" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="11_10">GD</named-content></p></list-item></list>¶
<boxed-text data-remove-label="true" data-id="BLK_BWL2" insert-citation="false" data-new-float="true"><caption><title data-id="BWL2">test-caption</title></caption><p>Test - Box Text</p><fn-group><fn data-class="jrnlBoxFoot"><p>Test - Box footnote</p></fn></fn-group></boxed-text><p data-class="jrnlSecPara"><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="ABBR" data-tag-type="ABBR" data-offset="31" data-match=" (GDM)" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="11_10">M</named-content>) increases maternal and neonatal morbidity. The Hyperglycaemia and Adverse Pregnancy Outcomes study detected a continuous relationship between maternal hyp<named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preeditor 4b5360d3-99b8-4ec9-a146-5a08ed957262">∂</named-content>erglycaemia and the incidence of perinatal complications.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R1 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="248" data-match="1" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="11_1" data-track-change="1"><sup>1</sup></xref> Even a mildly-increased glycemia can have a negative impact on both the mother and <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">foetus</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="HIGH" data-tag-type="HIGH" data-offset="335" data-match="foetus" data-replace="fetus" data-pattern="fetus" data-tag-index="11_11" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="foetus">fetus</named-content>.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R1 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="343" data-match="1" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="11_2" data-track-change="1"><sup>1</sup></xref> Based on these findings, new diagnostic criteria of GDM were proposed.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R2 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="418" data-match="2" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="11_3" data-track-change="2"><sup>2</sup></xref> Application of these criteria has increased the prevalence of GDM to <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="APP,PRE,PREP,RNG,SUF,SREP,UNT" data-tag-type="PRE" data-offset="491" data-track-change="-">–</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="APP,PRE,PREP,RNG,SUF,SREP,UNT" data-tag-type="SUF" data-offset="494" data-tag-desc="APP,PRE,PREP,RNG,SUF,SREP,UNT" data-tag-type="SREP" data-offset="497" data-match="10-25 %" data-replace="%" data-pattern="$6" data-tag-index="11_8">%</named-content> of gestations.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R3 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="514" data-match="3" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="11_4" data-track-change="3"><sup>3</sup></xref> Given its high prevalence and<xref ref-type="fig" data-citation-string=" F4 " data-init-id="F4" data-cite-type="insert" data-track="del" data-anchor="true"><inline-graphic data-id="img1" data-track="ins" data-selector-jrnlfigure=".//*[contains(@class, 'jrnlFigure')][not(@data-track='del')]" data-selector-jrnlinlinefigure=".//*[contains(@class, 'jrnlInlineFigure')][not(@data-track='del')]" data-validate="requiredResource" data-check-attr="src" data-original-name="profile"
