data-track="ins" data-anchor="true">figures 4 and 5</xref> negative pregnancy outcomes, GDM is an important public health issue. Therefore, a need exists to treat more women during pregnancy.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R4 R5 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="681" data-match="4,5" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="11_5" data-track-change="4,5"><sup>4 5</sup></xref> Treatment of a higher number of pregnant women in turn has been associated with improved perinatal outcomes, and is cost-effective.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R4 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="819" data-match="4" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="11_6" data-track-change="4"><sup>4</sup></xref> The treatment of GDM has been reported to reduce perinatal morbidity as compared with routine prenatal care.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R6 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="932" data-match="6" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="11_7" data-track-change="6"><sup>6</sup></xref> However, whether the intervention can make pregnancy outcomes comparable to those of women without GDM remains unknown.</p><fig data-id="BLK_F4" data-new-float="true" data-stream-name="a_F4" position="float" fig-type="figure"><label>Figure 4</label><caption><title data-id="F4"/></caption><graphic data-primary-extension="jpeg" data-original-name="profile" data-filesize="5050B" data-colorspace="sRGB" data-geometry="222x227+0+0"/><fn data-class="jrnlFigFoot"><p>none</p></fn></fig><fig data-id="BLK_F5" data-new-float="true" data-stream-name="a_F5" position="float" fig-type="figure"><label>Figure 5</label><caption><title data-id="F5"/></caption><graphic data-primary-extension="jpeg" data-original-name="profile" data-filesize="5050B" data-colorspace="sRGB" data-geometry="222x227+0+0"/><fn data-class="jrnlFigFoot"><p>none</p></fn></fig><disp-quote><p><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="0" data-match="Medical Nutrition Therapy" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="MNT">Medical Nutrition Therapy</named-content> (<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="ABBR" data-tag-type="ABBR" data-offset="27" data-match=" (MNT)" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="12_5">MNT</named-content>) is first-line therapy in the treatment of GDM.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R7 R8 R9 R10 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="79" data-match="7–10" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="12_1" data-track-change="7&amp;ndash;10"><sup>7–10</sup></xref> Different types of dietary interventions have been compared and evaluated, with inconsistent results.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R11 R12 R13 R14 R15 R16 R17 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="190" data-match="11–17" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="12_2" data-track-change="11&amp;ndash;17"><sup>11–17</sup></xref>The lack of consistent data does not permit evidence-based recommendations, specifically with regards to macronutrient distribution of MNT in GDM management.</p><p>Restricting carbohydrates has been the cornerstone to GDM treatment. However, a less restrictive approach, permitting a higher consumption of complex carbohydrates is being studied as a possible alternative. A Higher–Complex Carbohydrate/Lower Fat <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VERSUS" data-tag-type="VERSUS" data-offset="250" data-match="versus" data-replace="vs" data-pattern="vs" data-tag-index="13_7" data-track-change="versus">v<named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preeditor e08e910d-c111-44ed-9f81-d3874d44cbda" data-track-detail="">ersu</named-content>s</named-content> a Low-Carbohydrate/Higher-Fat seems to improve maternal insulin resistance and infant adiposity.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R11 R12 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="354" data-match="11,12" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="13_1" data-track-change="11,12"><sup>11 12</sup></xref> In parallel, low glycemic-index diets are have also shown benefits in maternal insulin resistance, a lower need of insulin usage and risk of macrosomia.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R15 R16 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="514" data-match="15,16" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="13_2" data-track-change="15,16"><sup>15 16</sup></xref> Consensus panels have not given specific diet recommendations due to this insufficient evidence. However, both the American College of Obstetricians and <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">Gynecologists</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="SPELL" data-tag-type="SPELL" data-offset="675" data-match="Gynecologists" data-replace="Gynaecologists" data-pattern="Gynaecologists" data-tag-index="13_8" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="Gynecologists">Gynaecologists</named-content> (<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="ABBR" data-tag-type="ABBR" data-offset="690" data-match=" (ACOG)" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="13_4">ACOG</named-content>) and Endocrine Society still stand behind low fat diets in GDM treatment. A very recent metanalysis that included 18 <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">randomized</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="SPELL" data-tag-type="SPELL" data-offset="812" data-match="randomized" data-replace="randomised" data-pattern="randomised" data-tag-index="13_9" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="randomized">randomised</named-content> controlled trials showed that dietary interventions as <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">compared to</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="HIGH" data-tag-type="HIGH" data-offset="878" data-match="compared to" data-replace="compared with" data-pattern="compared with" data-tag-index="13_6" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="compared to">compared with</named-content> routine care in GDM management improved perinatal outcomes.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R18 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="950" data-match="18" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="13_3" data-track-change="18"><sup>18</sup></xref> It highlights the importance of nutritional approaches in GDM treatment and the need to evaluate further its effect on perinatal outcomes in order to find the most appropriate MNT.</p><p>The numerous health benefits of the Mediterranean Diet (MedDiet), with a high consumption of extra virgin olive oil and nuts, has been repeatedly reproduced.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R19 R20 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="158" data-match="19,20" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="14_1" data-track-change="19,20"><sup>19 20</sup></xref> A MedDiet-based MNT needs to be examined since it is a diet that has a low-carbohydrate/higher-fat macronutrient distribution, has a low glycaemic index diet and is rich in antioxidants and anti-inflammatory components.</p></disp-quote>¶
¶
¶
¶
¶
<disp-quote data-type="pull-quote"><p>In healthy pregnant women, the adherence to this dietary pattern has been associated with a <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="92" data-match="30%" data-replace="30" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="15_3">30</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="UNT" data-offset="94" data-match="30%" data-replace="%" data-pattern="%" data-tag-index="15_3">%</named-content> reduction in the incidence of GDM, as well as a reduction in adverse perinatal outcomes.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R21 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="185" data-match="21" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="15_1" data-track-change="21"><sup>21</sup></xref> Most studies evaluating MNT focus their attention in assessing different types of MNT as <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">compared to</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="HIGH" data-tag-type="HIGH" data-offset="279" data-match="compared to" data-replace="compared with" data-pattern="compared with" data-tag-index="15_5" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="compared to">compared with</named-content> standard-care diets in women with GDM. Only one study group have compared women with <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="376" data-match="normal glucose tolerance" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="NGT">normal glucose tolerance</named-content> (<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="ABBR" data-tag-type="ABBR" data-offset="402" data-match=" (NGT)" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="15_4">NGT</named-content>) to women with GDM treated with diet and exercise.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R22 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="457" data-match="22" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="15_2" data-track-change="22"><sup>22</sup></xref> There are no published studies evaluating the effect of a MedDiet-based MNT on GDM complications (glycaemic control and pregnancy outcomes) nor comparing these women with those with NGT.</p><p>The aim of this study was to explore clinical, biochemical and body weight parameters, as well as maternal and neonatal outcomes, of women with GDM treated with a MedDiet-based MNT <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VERSUS" data-tag-type="VERSUS" data-offset="181" data-match="versus" data-replace="vs" data-pattern="vs" data-tag-index="16_2" data-track-change="versus">v<named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preeditor e08e910d-c111-44ed-9f81-d3874d44cbda" data-track-detail="">ersu</named-content>s</named-content> women with NGT.</p></disp-quote>¶
<title data-level="1" data-class="jrnlHead1" old-class="">Research <named-content content-type="del" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-type="s-case">Designs</named-content><named-content content-type="ins" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-type="s-case">designs</named-content> and <named-content content-type="del" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-type="s-case">Methods</named-content><named-content content-type="ins" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-type="s-case">methods</named-content><named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">.</named-content></title>¶
<title data-level="2" data-class="jrnlHead2" old-class="">Trial <named-content content-type="del" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-type="s-case">Design</named-content><named-content content-type="ins" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-type="s-case">design</named-content><named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">.</named-content></title><disp-quote data-type="pull-quote"><p>The study was a secondary analysis of the St. Carlos GDM Prevention study – a prospective, single centre, <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">randomized</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="SPELL" data-tag-type="SPELL" data-offset="108" data-match="randomized" data-replace="randomised" data-pattern="randomised" data-tag-index="19_9" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="randomized">randomised</named-content> trial with two parallel groups. It targeted all pregnant women followed by the Obstetrics Department of the Hospital Clínico San Carlos (Madrid, Spain) from January <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">1st</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="ORDI" data-tag-type="ORDI" data-offset="285" data-match="1st" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="19_6" data-function="numberToText,addTrackChanges" data-track-change="1st">first</named-content> through December 31st, <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="THSE" data-tag-type="THSE" data-offset="312" data-match="2015" data-replace="2015" data-pattern="2015" data-tag-index="19_5">2015</named-content>. A detailed description of the <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="LQUOTE" data-tag-type="LQUOTE" data-offset="348" data-match="“" data-replace="“" data-pattern="“" data-tag-index="19_7"><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preeditor e08e910d-c111-44ed-9f81-d3874d44cbda" data-track-detail="">‘</named-content></named-content>St. Carlos Gestational GDM prevention study<named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preeditor e08e910d-c111-44ed-9f81-d3874d44cbda" data-track-detail="">’</named-content><span data-class="jrnlDeleted" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="RQUOTE" data-tag-type="RQUOTE" data-offset="394" data-match="”" data-replace="”" data-pattern="”" data-tag-index="19_8" data-track="del" data-modified="Remove empty tag"/> has been previously published.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R21 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="429" data-match="21" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="19_1" data-track-change="21"><sup>21</sup></xref> In summary, participants were <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">randomized</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="SPELL" data-tag-type="SPELL" data-offset="464" data-match="randomized" data-replace="randomised" data-pattern="randomised" data-tag-index="19_10" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="randomized">randomised</named-content> at 12<s> </s><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="481" data-match="gestational weeks" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="GW">gestational weeks</named-content> to a control or intervention group. At this point, the intervention started. The research team did not impose any nutritional recommendations on the control group. This group received nutritional recommendations provided in regular clinical practice by obstetricians and midwifes. Current guidelines recommend limiting the consumption of all fats which by default include extra virgin olive oil and nuts. In contrast, the intervention group were recommended to consume a daily intake of<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAR,OPR,VAL,OPRS,VALS,UNT" data-tag-type="OPR" data-offset="985" data-match="of ≥ 40ml" data-replace=" ≥" data-pattern=" $2" data-tag-index="19_2" data-track-change=" ≥ "> ≥</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAR,OPR,VAL,OPRS,VALS,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="990" data-match="of ≥ 40ml" data-replace="40" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="19_2">40</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAR,OPR,VAL,OPRS,VALS,UNT" data-tag-type="UNT" data-offset="992" data-match="of ≥ 40ml" data-replace=" mL" data-pattern=" $2" data-tag-index="19_2" data-track-change="ml"> mL</named-content> of extra virgin olive oil and a handful <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,RNGS,RNGC,RNGE,UNT" data-tag-type="RNGS" data-offset="1035" data-match="(25-30g" data-replace="(25" data-pattern="(25" data-tag-index="19_3">(25</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,RNGS,RNGC,RNGE,UNT" data-tag-type="RNGC" data-offset="1038" data-match="(25-30g" data-replace="–" data-pattern="–" data-tag-index="19_3" data-track-change="-">–</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,RNGS,RNGC,RNGE,UNT" data-tag-type="RNGE" data-offset="1039" data-match="(25-30g" data-replace="30" data-pattern="$4" data-tag-index="19_3">30</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,RNGS,RNGC,RNGE,UNT" data-tag-type="UNT" data-offset="1041" data-match="(25-30g" data-replace=" g" data-pattern=" $5" data-tag-index="19_3" data-track-change="g"> g</named-content>) of nuts.</p></disp-quote>¶
¶
<p data-class="jrnlSecPara">The study was approved by the Ethics Committee of Hospital Clínico San Carlos and conducted according to the Helsinki Declaration. All women signed a letter of informed consent. The study was registered at ISRCTN84389045.</p>¶

<title data-level="3" data-class="jrnlHead3" old-class="">GDM screening and treatment<named-content content-type="del cts-3" alt="preeditor 0cc3574f-ac88-4b19-968b-dc069b047c2c" data-track-detail="">.</named-content></title>¶
<p data-class="jrnlSecPara">GDM was diagnosed at <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,RNGS,RNGC,RNGE,UNT" data-tag-type="RNGS" data-offset="21" content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="59" data-match="2-h" data-replace="2" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="25_4">2</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="UNT" data-offset="60" data-match="2-h" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="UNT" data-offset="65" data-match="75-g" data-replace=" g" data-pattern=" $2" data-tag-index="25_5" data-track-change="-g"> g</named-content> <named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preeditor 2ebeacb3-1539-4652-8384-ad11baf93c2b" data-track-detail=""/>oral glucose tolerance test (IADPSG/WHO criteria.<xref data-track-change="2"><sup>2</sup></xref> Women from both the control and intervention groups that were diagnosed with GDM (177/874, 20%) were referred to the Diabetes and Pregnancy Unit and treated according to local guidelines.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R4 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="310" data-match="4" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="25_2" data-track-change="4"><sup>4</sup></xref> Regardless of having been previously allocated to the control or intervention group, all women who developed GDM received the same treatment.</p>¶
<p data-class="jrnlSecPara">Within <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">one</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="NUM,TIME" data-tag-type="NUM" data-offset="7" data-match="one week" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="26_7" data-function="textToNumber,addTrackChanges" data-track-change="one">1</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="NUM,TIME" data-tag-type="TIME" data-offset="10" data-match="one week" data-replace=" week" data-pattern=" $2" data-tag-index="26_7" data-track-change=" week"> week</named-content> of GDM diagnosis women had their first scheduled appointment at the Diabetes and Pregnancy Unit. <p data-class="jrnlSecPara">Women who did not develop GDM followed the recommendations assigned to them according to the group they were originally <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">randomized</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="SPELL" data-tag-type="SPELL" data-offset="120" data-match="randomized" data-replace="randomised" data-pattern="randomised" data-tag-index="28_1" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="randomized">randomised</named-content> to (control or intervention group).</p>¶
<title data-level="2" data-class="jrnlHead2" old-class="">Study outcomes<named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">.</named-content></title>¶
<p data-class="jrnlSecPara">The primary objective was to <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="HIGH" data-tag-type="HIGH" data-offset="29" data-match="compare" data-replace="compare" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="30_2" data-function="addTrackChanges">compare</named-content> glycaemic control (as determined by HbA<sub>1c</sub> levels at <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,RNGS,RNGC,RNGE,UNT" data-tag-type="RNGS" data-offset="89" data-match="36-38" data-replace="36" data-pattern="$2" data-tag-index="30_1">36</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,RNGS,RNGC,RNGE,UNT" data-tag-type="RNGC" data-offset="91" data-match="36-38" data-replace="–" data-pattern="–" data-tag-index="30_1" data-track-change="-">–</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,RNGS,RNGC,RNGE,UNT" data-tag-type="RNGE" data-offset="92" data-match="36-38" data-replace="38" data-pattern="$4" data-tag-index="30_1">38</named-content> <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="95" data-match="gestational weeks" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="GW">gestational weeks</named-content>) of women with and without GDM.</p>¶
<title data-level="1" data-class="jrnlHead1" old-class="">Secondary outcomes were<named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">:</named-content></title>¶
<list list-content="ol" list-type="order">¶
<list-item>¶
<p data-class="jrnlListPara" data-class-name="SecPara"><named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="" data-track-detail="">(<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R1 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="1" data-match="1" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="32_1" data-track-change="1"><sup>1</sup></xref></named-content><named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="" data-track-detail="">)</named-content>To <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="HIGH" data-tag-type="HIGH" data-offset="6" data-match="compare" data-replace="compare" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="32_25" data-function="addTrackChanges">compare</named-content> biochemical and clinical parameters (glucose, Insulin, HOMA-IR and blood pressure), lifestyle patterns and gestational weight gain between the GDM and NGT groups. Blood pressure was measured with an adequate armlet after the participants had been seated for <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="272" data-match="10 minutes" data-replace="10" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="32_17">10</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="UNT" data-offset="274" data-match="10 minutes" data-replace=" min" data-pattern=" min" data-tag-index="32_17" data-track-change=" minutes"> min</named-content>. Lifestyle was assessed using questionnaires evaluating physical activity, general healthy eating habits (Nutrition Score) and adherence to the MedDiet (MEDAS score), as described previously<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R21 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="475" data-match="21" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="32_2" data-track-change="21"><sup>21</sup></xref> The questionnaire used to obtain the Nutrition Score contains 15 items, 3 of which evaluate physical activity and 12 food frequency intakes. The Nutrition score objective is<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAR,OPR,VAL,OPRS,VALS,UNT" data-tag-type="OPR" data-offset="652" data-match="is &amp;gt;5" data-replace=" &gt;" data-pattern=" $2" data-tag-index="32_4" data-track-change=" &amp;gt;"> &gt;</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAR,OPR,VAL,OPRS,VALS,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="654" data-match="is &amp;gt;5" data-replace="5" data-pattern="$3" data-tag-index="32_4">5</named-content>.<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAR,OPR,VAL,OPRS,VALS,UNT" data-tag-type="OPR" data-offset="656" data-match=" +1" data-replace="+" data-pattern="$2" data-tag-index="32_5" data-track-change=" +">+</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAR,OPR,VAL,OPRS,VALS,UNT" data-tag-type="SNUM" data-offset="658" data-match=" +1" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="32_5">1</named-content> points is given to habits associated with diabetes mellitus 2 prevention and <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="HYPTOMIN,VAL" data-tag-type="HYPTOMIN" data-offset="737" data-match="-1" data-replace="−" data-pattern="−" data-tag-index="32_20" data-track-change="-">−</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="HYPTOMIN,VAL" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="738" data-match="-1" data-replace="1" data-pattern="$2" data-tag-index="32_20">1</named-content> points to those associated with increased risk. <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="SNUM" data-tag-type="SNUM" data-offset="788" data-match="0" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="32_23" data-function="numberToText,addTrackChanges">0</named-content> points are given when habits are associated with neither prevention nor risk; it is the minimum objective to be achieved. The MEDAS questionnaire evaluates 14 items. data-track-detail="">]</named-content> we have established the limit of non-inferiority based on the variability of the HbA1c levels in a large sample of pregnant women. The δ value represents the maximum difference tolerable value according to the variability of the parameter at week 12. Considering the current results and sample size <named-content content-type="del cts-3" alt="preeditor 0cc3574f-ac88-4b19-968b-dc069b047c2c" data-track-detail="">[</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-3" alt="preeditor 0cc3574f-ac88-4b19-968b-dc069b047c2c" data-track-detail="">(</named-content>mean GDM group: <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="472" data-match="5.31%" data-replace="5.31" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="35_11">5.31</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="UNT" data-offset="476" data-match="5.31%" data-replace="%" data-pattern="%" data-tag-index="35_11">%</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="PER,VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="477" data-match="5.31% (35 mmol/mol" data-replace=" (35" data-pattern=" $2" data-tag-index="35_2"> (35</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="PER,VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="PER,VAL,UNT" data-offset="481" data-match="5.31% (35 mmol/mol" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="35_2"> mmol/mol</named-content>); mean NGT group: <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="509" data-match="5.23%" data-replace="5.23" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="35_13">5.23</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="UNT" data-offset="513" data-match="5.23%" data-replace="%" data-pattern="%" data-tag-index="35_13">%</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="PER,VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="514" data-match="5.23% (34mmol/mol" data-replace=" (34" data-pattern=" $2" data-tag-index="35_3"> (34</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="PER,VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="PER,VAL,UNT" data-offset="518" data-match="5.23% (34mmol/mol" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="35_3">mmol/mol</named-content>)<named-content content-type="ins cts-3" alt="preeditor 0cc3574f-ac88-4b19-968b-dc069b047c2c" data-track-detail="">)</named-content><named-content content-type="del cts-3" alt="preeditor 0cc3574f-ac88-4b19-968b-dc069b047c2c" data-track-detail="">]</named-content>, a statistical power<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAR,OPR,VAL,OPRS,VALS,UNT" data-tag-type="OPR" data-offset="549" data-match="power &amp;gt; 99%" data-replace=" &gt;" data-pattern=" $2" data-tag-index="35_8" data-track-change=" &amp;gt; "> &gt;</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="552" data-match="99%" data-replace="99" data-pattern="$3" data-tag-index="35_8">99</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="UNT" data-offset="554" data-match="99%" data-replace="%" data-pattern="%" data-tag-index="35_15">%</named-content> permits assumption that treatment in the GDM group would be at least as efficacious as the NGT with a non-inferiority margin of −<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="687" data-match="0.2%" data-replace="0.2" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="35_16">0.2</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="UNT" data-offset="690" data-match="0.2%" data-replace="%" data-pattern="%" data-tag-index="35_16">%</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="PER,VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="691" data-match="0.2% (0.8 mmol/mol" data-replace=" (0.8" data-pattern=" $2" data-tag-index="35_4"> (0.8</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="PER,VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="PER,VAL,UNT" data-offset="696" data-match="0.2% (0.8 mmol/mol" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="35_4"> mmol/mol</named-content>).</p>¶
<title data-level="2" data-class="jrnlHead2" old-class="">Statistical analysis<named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">.</named-content></title>¶
<p data-class="jrnlSecPara">Discrete variables are presented with their frequency and percentage distribution, continuous variables by their mean and standard deviation (<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAR,OPR,VAL,OPRS,VALS,UNT" data-tag-type="OPR" data-offset="142" data-match="±SD" data-replace="±" data-pattern="$2" data-tag-index="37_1">±</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="ABBRV" data-tag-type="ABBRV" data-offset="144" data-match="SD" data-replace="SD" data-pattern="SD" data-tag-index="37_2" data-function="addTrackChanges">SD</named-content>) when normally distributed, and with median and <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">interquartile range</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="ABBRV" data-tag-type="ABBRV" data-offset="195" data-match="interquartile range" data-replace="IQR" data-pattern="IQR" data-tag-index="37_3" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="interquartile range">IQR</named-content> when not. All primary analyses were performed on an intention-to-treat basis. Comparison between groups for categorical variables was evaluated using the χ<sup>2</sup> test or Fisher's exact test. For continuous variables, measures were compared with Student’s t test or the Mann–Whitney U test if distribution of quantitative variables was not normal, as verified by the Shapiro-Wilk test.</p>¶
<p data-class="jrnlSecPara">The magnitude of association between study groups and binary outcomes was evaluated using the <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">odds ratio (OR)</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="ABBRV" data-tag-type="ABBRV" data-offset="94" data-match="odds ratio (OR)" data-replace="OR" data-pattern="OR" data-tag-index="38_4" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="odds ratio (OR)">OR</named-content> and 95% <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">confidence interval (CI)</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="ABBRV" data-tag-type="ABBRV" data-offset="118" data-match="confidence interval (CI)" data-replace="CI" data-pattern="CI" data-tag-index="38_5" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="confidence interval (CI)">CI</named-content>.</p>¶
<p data-class="jrnlSecPara">For the primary efficacy endpoint, HbA<sub>1c</sub> levels at <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,RNGS,RNGC,RNGE,UNT" data-tag-type="RNGS" data-offset="51" data-match="36-38" data-replace="36" data-pattern="$2" data-tag-index="39_2">36</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,RNGS,RNGC,RNGE,UNT" data-tag-type="RNGC" data-offset="53" data-match="36-38" data-replace="–" data-pattern="–" data-tag-index="39_2" data-track-change="-">–</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,RNGS,RNGC,RNGE,UNT" data-tag-type="RNGE" data-offset="54" data-match="36-38" data-replace="38" data-pattern="$4" data-tag-index="39_2">38</named-content> <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="57" data-match="gestational weeks" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="GW">gestational weeks</named-content>, the comparison between groups was assessed using analysis of covariance (<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="ABBR" data-tag-type="ABBR" data-offset="149" data-match=" (ANCOVA)" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="39_7">ANCOVA</named-content>)Non-inferiority of GDM group was demonstrated if the two-sided <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="219" data-match="95%" data-replace="95" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="39_3">95</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="UNT" data-offset="221" data-match="95%" data-replace="%" data-pattern="%" data-tag-index="39_3">%</named-content> confidence interval (<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="244" data-match="95% CI" data-replace="95%" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="39_4">95%</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="UNT" data-offset="247" data-match="95% CI" data-replace=" CI" data-pattern=" $2" data-tag-index="39_4" data-track-change=" CI"> CI</named-content>) for the difference between the HbA<sub>1c</sub> means was above the pre-defined non-inferiority margin of −<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="350" data-match="0.2%" data-replace="0.2" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="39_5">0.2</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="UNT" data-offset="353" data-match="0.2%" data-replace="%" data-pattern="%" data-tag-index="39_5">%</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="PER,VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="354" data-match="0.2% (0.8 mmol/mol" data-replace=" (0.8" data-pattern=" $2" data-tag-index="39_1"> (0.8</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="PER,VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="PER,VAL,UNT" data-offset="359" data-match="0.2% (0.8 mmol/mol" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="39_1"> mmol/mol</named-content>).</p>¶
<p data-class="jrnlSecPara">Logistic regression analyses were used to assess the effect of the GDM for the secondary binary outcomes. Crude and adjusted models were fitted adjusted for BMI (continuous) and ethnicity. To evaluate the effect of the study group on the association of diabetes with the secondary outcome variables, the interaction term was introduced in the model.</p>¶
<p data-class="jrnlSecPara">All <italic>P</italic> values are 2-tailed at less than 0.05. Analyses were performed using SPSS, version 21 (Chicago, Illinois).</p>¶
<title data-level="1" data-class="jrnlHead1" old-class="">Results</title>¶
<title data-level="2" data-class="jrnlHead2" old-class="">Participant’s characteristics<named-content content-type="del cts-3" alt="preeditor 0cc3574f-ac88-4b19-968b-dc069b047c2c" data-track-detail="">.</named-content></title>¶
<p data-class="jrnlSecPara">In the St. Carlos GDM Prevention study, a total of <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="THSE" data-tag-type="THSE" data-offset="51" data-match="1501" data-replace="1501" data-pattern="1501" data-tag-index="44_6">1501</named-content> women attending their first ultrasound visit were eligible; <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="THSE" data-tag-type="THSE" data-offset="116" data-match="1000" data-replace="1000" data-pattern="1000" data-tag-index="44_7">1000</named-content> accepted participation and signed the consent form. They were randomly allocated to the control (<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAR,OPR,VAL,OPRS,VALS,UNT" data-tag-type="VAR" data-offset="218" data-match="n=500" data-replace="n" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="44_4" data-function="lowercase,removeItalics">n</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAR,OPR,VAL,OPRS,VALS,UNT" data-tag-type="OPR" data-offset="219" data-match="n=500" data-replace="=" data-pattern="$2" data-tag-index="44_4">=</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAR,OPR,VAL,OPRS,VALS,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="220" data-match="n=500" data-replace="500" data-pattern="$3" data-tag-index="44_4">500</named-content>) or intervention group (<named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAR,OPR,VAL,OPRS,VALS,UNT" data-tag-type="VAR" data-offset="248" data-match="n=500" data-replace="n" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="44_5" data-function="lowercase,removeItalics">n</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAR,OPR,VAL,OPRS,VALS,UNT" data-tag-type="OPR" data-offset="249" data-match="n=500" data-replace="=" data-pattern="$2" data-tag-index="44_5">=</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAR,OPR,VAL,OPRS,VALS,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="250" data-match="n=500" data-replace="500" data-pattern="$3" data-tag-index="44_5">500</named-content>). Sixty women in the control group and 66 women in the intervention group were lost to follow-up before GDM screening. Consequently, 874 women were followed through postpartum discharge and included in the final analysis. A total of <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="PER,VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="PER" data-offset="487" data-match="177 (20%" data-replace="177" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="44_2">177</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="PER,VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="490" data-match="177 (20%" data-replace=" (20%" data-pattern=" $2" data-tag-index="44_2"> (20%</named-content>, 103 from control group and 74 from intervention group) developed GDM and the remaining <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="PER,VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="PER" data-offset="584" data-match="697 (80%" data-replace="697" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="44_3">697</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="PER,VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="587" data-match="697 (80%" data-replace=" (80%" data-pattern=" $2" data-tag-index="44_3"> (80%</named-content>, 337 from control group and 360 from intervention group) had NGT (<xref ref-type="supplementary-material" data-citation-string=" " data-tag-desc="SUPPLFTREF" data-tag-type="SUPPLFTREF" data-offset="659" data-match="Supplemental Figure S1" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="44_1" data-track="del">Supplemental Figure S1</xref><xref ref-type="supplementary-material" data-citation-string=" SP2 " data-track="ins">online supplementary file 2</xref><xref ref-type="supplementary-material" data-citation-string=" ST1 " data-cite-type="delete" data-anchor="true">online supplementary table 1</xref><named-content content-type="del cts-3" alt="preeditor 0cc3574f-ac88-4b19-968b-dc069b047c2c" data-track-detail="">)</named-content>. These were included in this secondary analysis.</p>¶
<p data-class="jrnlSecPara"><xref ref-type="table" data-citation-string=" T1 " data-offset="0" data-match="Table 1" data-track="del"><named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">Table 1</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail=""><named-content content-type="changeCase sty cts-3" alt="preeditor 0cc3574f-ac88-4b19-968b-dc069b047c2c" data-track-detail="" data-track-hint="UPPERCASE Added">T<span data-class="hidden" hidden-track="track">t</span></named-content>able 1</named-content></xref><xref ref-type="table" data-citation-string=" T1 T2 " data-init-id="T1,T2" data-track="ins" data-cite-type="insert" data-anchor="true">Tables 1 and 2</xref> shows baseline demographic and clinical characteristics of the women of the two cohorts, according to glucose tolerance. Women with GDM had a higher pregestational BMI, fasting glucose, triglyceride levels and systolic blood pressure (all <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAR,OPR,VAL,OPRS,VALS,UNT" data-tag-type="VAR" data-offset="247" data-match="P&amp;lt;0.05" data-replace="&lt;i&gt;P&lt;/i&gt;" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="45_2" data-function="lowercase,removeItalics" data-track-change="&lt;i&gt;P&lt;/i&gt;">P</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAR,OPR,VAL,OPRS,VALS,UNT" data-tag-type="OPR" data-offset="248" data-match="P&amp;lt;0.05" data-replace="&lt;" data-pattern="$2" data-tag-index="45_2">&lt;</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAR,OPR,VAL,OPRS,VALS,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="249" data-match="P&amp;lt;0.05" data-replace="0.05" data-pattern="$3" data-tag-index="45_2">0.05</named-content>). Primary outcome.</p>¶

<title data-level="1" data-class="jrnlHead1" old-class="">Conclusions<named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">.</named-content></title>¶
<p data-class="jrnlSecPara">After <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="6" data-match="3 months" data-replace="3" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="54_2">3</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="UNT" data-offset="7" data-match="3 months" data-replace=" months" data-pattern=" $2" data-tag-index="54_2"> months</named-content> of treatment with a MedDiet as MNT, glycaemic control (measured by HbA1c) in GDMw was not inferior to that of NGTw. To our knowledge, this is the first study that shows that with GDM management, using a MedDiet-based MNT, GDMw had similar glycaemic control at <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,RNGS,RNGC,RNGE,UNT" data-tag-type="RNGS" data-offset="275" data-match="36-38" data-replace="36" data-pattern="$2" data-tag-index="54_1">36</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,RNGS,RNGC,RNGE,UNT" data-tag-type="RNGC" data-offset="277" data-match="36-38" data-replace="–" data-pattern="–" data-tag-index="54_1" data-track-change="-">–</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,RNGS,RNGC,RNGE,UNT" data-tag-type="RNGE" data-offset="278" data-match="36-38" data-replace="38" data-pattern="$4" data-tag-index="54_1">38</named-content> <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="281" data-match="gestational weeks" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="GW">gestational weeks</named-content> to NGTw. As expected given glycaemic control, no significant differences were observed in the rates of excessive weight gain, pregnancy induced hypertension, type of delivery, perineal trauma, prematurity and LGA new-borns when comparing GDMw and NGTw.</p>¶
<p data-class="jrnlSecPara">Only <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="5" data-match="27%" data-replace="27" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="55_3">27</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="UNT" data-offset="7" data-match="27%" data-replace="%" data-pattern="%" data-tag-index="55_3">%</named-content> of GDMw needed insulin therapy after failure of MNT. This observed rate is lower than rates described in other studies, around <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="136" data-match="56.7%" data-replace="56.7" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="55_4">56.7</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="UNT" data-offset="140" data-match="56.7%" data-replace="%" data-pattern="%" data-tag-index="55_4">%</named-content> in Caucasian women<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="162" data-match="26" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="55_1" data-citation-string=" R26 " data-track-change="26"><sup>26</sup></xref> and <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="VAL" data-offset="170" data-match="50%" data-replace="50" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="55_5">50</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,UNT" data-tag-type="UNT" data-offset="172" data-match="50%" data-replace="%" data-pattern="%" data-tag-index="55_5">%</named-content> in other regions of Spain.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="201" data-match="27" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="55_2" data-citation-string=" R27 " data-track-change="27"><sup>27</sup></xref></p>¶
<p data-class="jrnlSecPara">A continuous relationship between maternal glycemia and adverse maternal and neonatal outcomes is well documented.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="115" data-match="1" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="56_1" data-citation-string=" R1 " data-track-change="1"><sup>1</sup></xref> LGA new-borns, macrosomia and C-sections are the outcomes most linked to GDM and poor glycaemic control, as well as to maternal obesity and gestational weight gain<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="284" data-match="28-31" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="56_2" data-citation-string=" R28 R29 R30 R31 " data-track-change="28-31"><sup>28–31</sup></xref> In a large prospective study, high maternal BMI rather than hyperglycaemia was associated with LGA new-borns.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="401" data-match="32" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="56_3" data-citation-string=" R32 " data-track-change="32"><sup>32</sup></xref> However, our results revealed that, despite GDMw having a higher BMI at baseline, LGA and macrosomia rates were similar in GDMw and NGTw. Therefore, GDM management, that includes a MedDiet-based MNT, is associated with a lower incidence of these outcomes, possibly by inducing lower rates of excessive weight gain.</p>¶
<p data-class="jrnlSecPara">Most of the adverse pregnancy outcomes evaluated were similar between GDMw and NGTw. However, rates of NICU admissions, <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="120" data-match="insufficient weight gain" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="IWG">insufficient weight gain</named-content>, SGA new-borns and urinary tract infections were higher in the GDMw. The higher rates of NICU admission are concurrent with results from a retrospective cohort.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="306" data-match="22" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="57_1" data-citation-string=" R22 " data-track-change="22"><sup>22</sup></xref></p>¶
<p data-class="jrnlSecPara">While rates of excessive weight gain were lower in the GDMw than in NGTw, rates of <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="83" data-match="insufficient weight gain" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="IWG">insufficient weight gain</named-content> were significantly higher. One possible explanation is that following GDM diagnosis and, consequently, the care and advise provided women reduce energy intake, substituting high energy-dense foods for healthier food options.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="333" data-match="7" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="58_1" data-citation-string=" R7 " data-track-change="7"><sup>7</sup></xref> Another potential explanation is the fact that GDMw self-monitor blood glucose. Undoubtedly, it is an indispensable tool in improving glycaemic control and permits the tailoring of MNT to each individual.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="542" data-match="33" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="58_2" data-citation-string=" R33 " data-track-change="33"><sup>33</sup></xref> However, the downside of self-monitoring blood glucose is women’s attitude towards not achieving tight glycaemic control and concern that hyperglycaemia could lead to insulin therapy<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="733" data-match="34,35" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="58_3" data-citation-string=" R34 R35 " data-track-change="34,35"><sup>34 35</sup></xref> Women could thus restrict the consumption of the foods associated with higher glucose levels, and limit carbohydrate/caloric intake. In fact, when present, <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="896" data-match="insufficient weight gain" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="IWG">insufficient weight gain</named-content> occurred within the first weeks of self-monitoring of blood glucose, prior to insulin initiation, and therefore did not seem to be related to insulin therapy <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="FNW" data-tag-type="FNW" data-offset="1079" data-match="per se" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="58_4" data-function="removeItalics">per se</named-content> (Data not shown).</p>¶
<p data-class="jrnlSecPara">Determining appropriate gestational weight gain in overweight and obese women is an ongoing debate<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="100" data-match="12,13,23,36-38" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="59_1" data-citation-string=" R12 R13 R23 R36 R37 R38 " data-track-change="12,13,23,36-38"><sup>12 13 23 36–38</sup></xref> There is rising evidence that a lower gestational weight gain than that recommended by the Institute of Medicine in overweight and obese women reduces the risk for LGA neonates, macrosomia, preeclampsia and c-sections<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="335" data-match="37" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="59_2" data-citation-string=" R37 " data-track-change="37"><sup>37</sup></xref> A systematic review and meta-analysis reported higher rates of SGA and lower rates of LGA in overweight women who lost weight during pregnancy.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="483" data-match="23" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="59_3" data-citation-string=" R23 " data-track-change="23"><sup>23</sup></xref> Similarly, a recent systematic review and meta-analysis associated <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="555" data-match="insufficient weight gain" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="IWG">insufficient weight gain</named-content> with higher rates of SGA and prematurity and with lower rates of LGA and macrosomia.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="665" data-match="31" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="59_4" data-citation-string=" R31 " data-track-change="31"><sup>31</sup></xref> These data agree with those reported in the present study. The effect of <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="743" data-match="insufficient weight gain" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="IWG">insufficient weight gain</named-content> on SGA is still controversial and needs to be further studied. In any case, given the higher rates of <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="870" data-match="insufficient weight gain" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="IWG">insufficient weight gain</named-content> and SGA new-borns we have found strategies should be designed to try to avoid the occurrence of both.</p>¶
<p data-class="jrnlSecPara">Rates of urinary tract infections were significantly higher in GDMw than in NGTw. Maternal urinary tract infections could have facilitated higher rates of SGA new-borns, since they have been independently associated with prematurity and restricted intrauterine growth<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R39 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="269" data-match="39" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="60_1" data-track-change="39"><sup>39</sup></xref> In addition, women who had urinary tract infections required antibiotic treatment, potentially leading to changes in the microbiota that could induce higher rates of SGA new-borns<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R40 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="454" data-match="40" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="60_2" data-track-change="40"><sup>40</sup></xref> Furthermore, E.coli has been associated with SGA new-borns secondary to placental insufficiency and a higher risk of prematurity<xref ref-type="bibr" data-citation-string=" R41 R42 " data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="588" data-match="41,42" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="60_3" data-track-change="41,42"><sup>41 42</sup></xref></p>¶
<p data-class="jrnlSecPara">As <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">compared to</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="HIGH" data-tag-type="HIGH" data-offset="3" data-match="compared to" data-replace="compared with" data-pattern="compared with" data-tag-index="61_8" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="compared to">compared with</named-content> other studies, our rates of insulin therapy were the lowest. A low-carbohydrate diet, with a carbohydrate content of 40%, similar to ours, was not associated with lower rates on insulin treatments as <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">compared to</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="HIGH" data-tag-type="HIGH" data-offset="215" data-match="compared to" data-replace="compared with" data-pattern="compared with" data-tag-index="61_9" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="compared to">compared with</named-content> a control diet in women with GDM.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="261" data-match="27" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="61_1" data-citation-string=" R27 " data-track-change="27"><sup>27</sup></xref> In addition, pregnancy outcomes were found to be similar between groups. Rates of SGA, macrosomia, c-sections and maternal hypertension were lower in our group of women with GDM as <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">compared to</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="HIGH" data-tag-type="HIGH" data-offset="447" data-match="compared to" data-replace="compared with" data-pattern="compared with" data-tag-index="61_10" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="compared to">compared with</named-content> women allocated to the low-carbohydrate diet.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="505" data-match="27" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="61_2" data-citation-string=" R27 " data-track-change="27"><sup>27</sup></xref> This is so despite similarities in total caloric distribution of carbohydrates in our study and theirs. These differences could be attributed to the quality of fats consumed by our subjects, whose diet was rich in EVOO and nuts. They could also be attributed to the high content in fruits and vegetables. In fact, a recent systematic review and metanalysis revealed that using DASH diets as MNT in GDM was associated with improvements in HOMA-IR, medication need and macrosomia.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="990" data-match="18" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="61_3" data-citation-string=" R18 " data-track-change="18"><sup>18</sup></xref> Moreover, low glycaemic index diets have shown to reduce <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">birthweight</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="HIGH" data-tag-type="HIGH" data-offset="1052" data-match="birthweight" data-replace="birth weight" data-pattern="birth weight" data-tag-index="61_11" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="birthweight">birth weight</named-content>, risk of macrosomia and need for medication. However, results from studies testing different dietary interventions in GDM treatment indicate that mean <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">birthweight</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="HIGH" data-tag-type="HIGH" data-offset="1215" data-match="birthweight" data-replace="birth weight" data-pattern="birth weight" data-tag-index="61_12" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="birthweight">birth weight</named-content> in their studied sample was found to be higher than the one found in our women with GDM, including those following a low carbohydrate<sup>12</sup> and low-glycaemic index diet.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="1393" data-match="17" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="61_4" data-citation-string=" R17 " data-track-change="17"><sup>17</sup></xref> Yamamoto <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="ETL" data-tag-type="ETL" data-offset="1407" data-match="et al" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="61_6" data-function="addItalics" data-track-change="et al"><italic>et al</italic></named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="ETLDOT" data-tag-type="ETLDOT" data-offset="1412" data-match="." data-replace="delete" data-pattern="delete" data-tag-index="61_7"><named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">.</named-content></named-content>, concluded that neither a fat-modification nor low-carbohydrate diet modifies outcomes such as HbA1c, HOMA-IR, insulin need, or neonatal <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">birthweight</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="HIGH" data-tag-type="HIGH" data-offset="1551" data-match="birthweight" data-replace="birth weight" data-pattern="birth weight" data-tag-index="61_13" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="birthweight">birth weight</named-content>, macrosomia and large-for-gestational-age.<xref ref-type="bibr" data-tag-desc="BIBREF" data-tag-type="BIBREF" data-offset="1606" data-match="18" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="61_5" data-citation-string=" R18 " data-track-change="18"><sup>18</sup></xref> However, our results show that levels of HbA1c and HOMA-IR after GDM diagnosis and treatment is comparable to that of healthy women without GDM and so were rates of <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">birthweight</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="HIGH" data-tag-type="HIGH" data-offset="1776" data-match="birthweight" data-replace="birth weight" data-pattern="birth weight" data-tag-index="61_14" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="birthweight">birth weight</named-content>, rates of macrosomia and LGA.</p>¶
<p data-class="jrnlSecPara">While our study does not <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="HIGH" data-tag-type="HIGH" data-offset="25" data-match="compare" data-replace="compare" data-pattern="$1" data-tag-index="62_1" data-function="addTrackChanges">compare</named-content> one nutritional approach to another in GDM treatment, the maternofoetal outcomes found in our study seem to be promising when <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">compared to</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="HIGH" data-tag-type="HIGH" data-offset="159" data-match="compared to" data-replace="compared with" data-pattern="compared with" data-tag-index="62_2" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="compared to">compared with</named-content> those found in other studies that used different types MNT. It is important to consider that our results are being <named-content content-type="del cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="">compared to</named-content><named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preediting" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="HIGH" data-tag-type="HIGH" data-offset="286" data-match="compared to" data-replace="compared with" data-pattern="compared with" data-tag-index="62_3" data-function="addTrackChanges" data-track-change="compared to">compared with</named-content> studies whose population were mainly women of high risk - mostly high BMI and/or metabolic risk factors<s fontsize="12.0">. </s>This means that baseline characteristics between our group of women are not like those of others and therefore making comparisons of our outcomes to that of others is not accurate enough</p>¶
<p data-class="jrnlSecPara">This study seems to suggest that MNT based on a MedDiet enhanced with extra virgin olive oil and nuts, thus with a high fat content, is associated with glycaemic control and with a reduction in GDM-related adverse perinatal outcomes. Further studies are needed to confirm our findings. It would be ideal to conduct a RCT specifically designed to evaluate the effect of a MedDiet MNT on glycaemic control and perinatal outcomes in addition to assessing the cause of IWG in GDM women.</p>¶
<title data-level="1" data-class="jrnlHead1" old-class="">Limitations<named-content content-type="del cts-3" alt="preeditor 0cc3574f-ac88-4b19-968b-dc069b047c2c" data-track-detail="">.</named-content></title>¶
<p data-class="jrnlSecPara">Some limitations were found in this study. First, this was a post-hoc analysis and therefore the original objective of the study was not to evaluate the efficacy of MNT in controlling glycemia in GDMw. Moreover, the data available of the diet of pregnant women gives qualitative rather than quantitative information. Exact caloric and macronutrient intake is lacking because in GDM management women are not provided with a diet with a specific daily total caloric intake. They are given nutritional counselling on what foods to eat and the approximate quantity in which they should eat them, not a strict meal plan. Another limitation is that some of the GDMw had been allocated to the intervention group, prior to GDM diagnosis. The nutritional recommendations given to women of the intervention group were like the ones provided in GDM management. Therefore, women belonging to the intervention group who later developed GDM<named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preeditor 2ebeacb3-1539-4652-8384-ad11baf93c2b" data-track-detail="">(<xref ref-type="fig" data-citation-string=" F2 " data-cite-type="insert" data-anchor="true" data-track="del">figure 2</xref><xref ref-type="fig" data-citation-string=" F1 " data-track="ins" data-cite-type="insert">figure 1</xref><named-content data-class="jrnlQueryRef" data-type="end" content-type="jrnlQueryRef"/><named-content data-class="jrnlQueryRef" data-type="end" content-type="jrnlQueryRef"/><named-content data-class="jrnlQueryRef" data-type="end" content-type="jrnlQueryRef"/>)</named-content> (77/177) had been following recommendations of MedDiet with enhanced consumption of extra virgin olive oil and pistachios for a longer period than those belonging to the<named-content content-type="ins cts-1" alt="preeditor 2ebeacb3-1539-4652-8384-ad11baf93c2b" data-track-detail="">(<xref ref-type="fig" data-citation-string=" F2 " data-cite-type="insert">figure 2</xref>)</named-content> control group. Nevertheless, we observed no interaction in perinatal outcomes between women of the control and intervention group who later developed GDM.</p>¶
<fig data-id="BLK_F1" data-stream-name="a_F1" data-new-float="true" data-page-num="4" data-position="bottom" data-top-gap="15pt" data-bot-gap="20pt" data-left-gap="12pt" data-right-gap="12pt" data-column-start="1" data-column-span="1" data-stack-with="BLK_T1" data-caption-inside-float="TopRight" data-float-percent="70" position="float" fig-type="figure"><label>Figure 1</label><caption><title data-id="F1">¶
<named-content data-class="jrnlQueryRef" data-type="start" data-query-ref="true" data-query-for="author" data-channel="query" data-topic="action" data-event="click" data-message="{'funcToCall': 'highlightQuery'}" data-query-action="uncited-figure" content-type="jrnlQueryRef" data-replied="true"/>¶
</title></caption><graphic data-primary-extension="png" data-original-name="confidentialComment-Assoc_editor" data-filesize="19.1KB" data-colorspace="sRGB" data-geometry="404x243+0+0"/><inline-graphic data-id="img1" data-track="ins" data-selector-jrnlfigure=".//*[contains(@class, 'jrnlFigure')][not(@data-track='del')]" data-selector-jrnlinlinefigure=".//*[contains(@class, 'jrnlInlineFigure')][not(@data-track='del')]" data-validate="requiredResource" data-check-attr="src" data-original-name="profile" data-filesize="5050B" data-colorspace="sRGB" data-geometry="222x227+0+0" data-primary-extension="jpeg"/></fig>¶
<fig data-id="BLK_F2" data-stream-name="a_F2" data-new-float="true" data-page-num="5" data-position="top" data-column-start="0" data-column-span="1" data-caption-inside-float="BottomLeft" data-caption-width="90" data-float-percent="140" position="float" fig-type="figure"><label>Figure 2</label><caption><title data-id="F2"/></caption><graphic data-primary-extension="tif" data-original-name="perfect" data-filesize="1.399MB" data-colorspace="sRGB" data-geometry="1772x1055+0+0"/></fig>¶
<p data-class="jrnlSecPara">In summary, comprehensive management of GDM, using a MedDiet-based MNT, is associated with the achievement of similar HbA1c levels at <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,RNGS,RNGC,RNGE,UNT" data-tag-type="RNGS" data-offset="134" data-match="36-38" data-replace="36" data-pattern="$2" data-tag-index="66_1">36</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,RNGS,RNGC,RNGE,UNT" data-tag-type="RNGC" data-offset="136" data-match="36-38" data-replace="–" data-pattern="–" data-tag-index="66_1" data-track-change="-">–</named-content><named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="VAL,RNGS,RNGC,RNGE,UNT" data-tag-type="RNGE" data-offset="137" data-match="36-38" data-replace="38" data-pattern="$4" data-tag-index="66_1">38</named-content> <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="140" data-match="gestational weeks" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="GW">gestational weeks</named-content> as that of women with NGT. Some GDM-related perinatal complications were not different between GDMw and NGTw. Notwithstanding the higher rates of SGA new-borns and <named-content content-type="jrnlPatterns" alt="" data-track-detail="" data-tag-desc="EXPN" data-tag-type="EXPN" data-offset="322" data-match="insufficient weight gain" data-pattern="" data-tag-index="" data-abbr="IWG">insufficient weight gain</named-content>, the fact that there were no differences in the rates of excessive weight gain, pregnancy induced hypertension, type of delivery, perineal trauma, prematurity and LGA new-borns is an important finding. This indicates the potential benefit of using this type of diet as MNT in women with GDM. However, strategies are needed to reduce the rates of SGA new-borns and IWG and, thus, avoid their deleterious consequences.</p>¶
